title: Short-Form PCL-5-8 (IPC Session 1)
description: Short-Form PCL-5-8 that is intended for IPC Session 1

item.text: A place to declare values that cannot be created using FHIRPath such as Coding. Retrieve the following items has answer value using variable expression, to use the declared value.
Observation ID of PC-PTSD Session 1 Score

Tip
The next set of questions are from a short version of the PTSD Checklist for DSM-5 (Short-Form PCL-5-8) These questions measure PTSD.

Example dialogue
"Now, I would like to ask you some questions to see if you have significant trauma in your life."

I am going to ask you about some problems that people sometimes have in response to a very stressful experience. Keeping your worst event in mind, please think of each problem carefully and then pick one of the answer options to indicate how much you have been bothered by that problem in the past month.

In the past month, how much were you bothered by:
Repeated, disturbing, and unwanted memories of the stressful experience?

In the past month, how much were you bothered by:
Avoiding external reminders of the stressful experience (for example, people, places, conversations, activities, objects, or situations)?

In the past month, how much were you bothered by:
Having strong negative beliefs about yourself, other people, or the world (for example, having thoughts such as: I am bad, there is something seriously wrong with me, no one can be trusted, the world is completely dangerous)?

In the past month, how much were you bothered by:
Feeling jumpy or easily startled?

In the past month, how much were you bothered by:
Feeling very upset when something reminded you of the stressful experience?

In the past month, how much were you bothered by:
Avoiding memories, thoughts, or feelings related to the stressful experience?

In the past month, how much were you bothered by:
Loss of interest in activities that you used to enjoy.

In the past month, how much were you bothered by:
Having difficulty concentrating?

Tip #1
List symptoms, describe severity (what the summed up scores mean), and impact on daily activities.

Tip #2
Please see severity levels for the Short-Form PCL-5-8:
• If the client scores a 8 or more, they may be experiencing challenges coping after a traumatic event.

Example dialogue
"Your score is an indication that the trauma you have is significantly impacting your life. This is something we may work on."
This score suggests that you may not be experiencing challenges coping after a traumatic event
This score suggests that you may be experiencing mild challenges coping after a traumatic event
This score suggests that you may be experiencing moderate challenges coping after a traumatic event
This score suggests that you may be experiencing severe challenges coping after a traumatic event
